Ashley Broomhall trekked to the summit of 3,560ft (1,085m) Snowdon in Snowdonia before tackling Ben Nevis.
It took him seven hours to walk up and down the 4,406ft (1,344m) Scottish peak near Fort William. On the way up he had a snowball fight with other walkers.
He now plans to walk 3,208ft (978m) Scafell Pike in the Lake District.
Mr Broomhall, from Whitchurch in Shropshire, has been doing the walks to raise money for Cancer Research UK.
He set himself the peaks challenge after his mother was diagnosed with cancer.
The 28-year-old has been a member of Star Wars costuming club the 501st UK Garrison for more than five years.
Members attend events across the UK dressed in "movie-accurate" costumes to raise funds for charity.
But Mr Broomhall had to make some modifications to his outfit to make it move more freely on the ascents and descents of Snowdon and Ben Nevis, which were done this summer.
For safety reasons, he wore walking boots because his costume footwear was not suitable for the terrain involved and was accompanied by friends.
Dressed as an Imperial stormtrooper and carrying a UK Garrison flag, Mr Broomhall said he drew more than his fair share of funny looks tackling Ben Nevis, Scotland highest Munro and Britain's tallest mountain.
He said: "We had been confusing a lot of other climbers along the way as a stormtrooper was the last thing they had been expecting to see climbing Ben Nevis.
"We handed out cards and told them my tale and they offered nothing but the most vocal support."
Mr Broomhall also received donations from other walkers.
Higher up Ben Nevis he had to negotiate thigh-deep snow.
At the first of these snowfields there was some light relief when he and his walking companion had a snowball fight with other walkers.
Mr Broomhall said: "The last snowfield held the summit and, with my heart swelling with pride, I let the flag fly and charged on to the summit.
"We had made it. It was brilliant and I was so happy at making it after all the struggles and rallying needed to get myself there.
"I was greeted by a cheer from the climbers there and planted the flag on the summit itself claiming it for the Empire."
He added: "I love Scotland and I love Munros and this was a challenge that I enjoyed doing.
"Scafell Pike is next. I've done the other two in armour, might as well do the third in it."

Jurors previously heard she was concerned 21 - month - old Ayeeshia Jane Smith may have had a seizure after taking drugs kept at the house . Ms Smith and ex - partner Matthew Rigby both deny murder . More on this and other stories from Stoke and Staffordshire The toddler , known as AJ , died in 2014 at the family home in St Giles Road, Burton-upon-Trent, following what the prosecution described as a "terrible assault". The court heard that AJ suffered "catastrophic" injuries, including a lacerated heart and internal bleeding, consistent with a severe impact. Post-mortem examinations revealed that Ayeeshia Jane Smith also had historic injuries, including a previous brain bleed and fractures to her ribs, consistent with her having been subjected to non-accidental harm on more than one occasion before her death.

Opening the prosecution's case, Christopher Hotten QC told the jury that both Ms Smith, 23, and Matthew Rigby, 21, were responsible for the fatal injuries inflicted upon AJ. He alleged that the couple, who were in a volatile relationship, had engaged in a "joint enterprise" to inflict serious harm, or that one had caused the injuries while the other failed to protect the child. The jury was presented with evidence of a chaotic household where drug use, including cannabis, was prevalent. Ms Smith's admission about using her limited income support to fund drug purchases underlined the difficult environment AJ was living in. The prosecution highlighted texts and calls between Ms Smith and Rigby in the hours leading up to AJ's death, which painted a picture of tension and concern about AJ's health, specifically the worry that she may have ingested drugs.

During cross-examination, Ms Smith maintained her innocence, accusing Matthew Rigby of being the one who inflicted the fatal injuries. She claimed she had briefly left the room and returned to find AJ unresponsive. Conversely, Rigby's defence team argued that it was Ms Smith who was responsible, suggesting she had a history of losing her temper and being violent. The court heard conflicting accounts from both defendants, each attempting to shift blame onto the other. Social services had been involved with the family prior to AJ's death, and concerns about the child's welfare had been raised on multiple occasions. Evidence presented included records of these interventions and assessments. The trial, presided over by Mr Justice Haddon-Cave at Stafford Crown Court, continues to hear from medical experts, police officers, and other witnesses who were involved in the investigation. The jury's task is to determine who was responsible for the tragic death of Ayeeshia Jane Smith, considering the complex web of evidence and conflicting narratives presented by the defence and prosecution. The deeply distressing nature of the case, involving a young child, has drawn significant public attention to the proceedings.

Police have launched a full investigation into the shocking incident and are appealing for witnesses. Detective Inspector Peter McFarlane, who is leading the inquiry, described the attack as "senseless and brutal." Detective Inspector McFarlane urged anyone who was in the Ardencraig Quadrant or Ardencraig Drive areas of Castlemilk, Glasgow, around the time of the incident to come forward. "We are particularly keen to speak to anyone who may have seen individuals acting suspiciously in the vicinity, or who may have dashcam footage or private CCTV that could assist our investigation," he added. "Even the smallest piece of information could prove vital in piecing together what happened and identifying the culprits. We understand that residents in Castlemilk will be concerned by this news, and I want to reassure the community that extensive enquiries are underway. Officers will be conducting high-visibility patrols in the area to provide reassurance."

From Winston Churchill's infamous visit to Belfast in 1912 to a 1963 Viking invasion re-enactment in a County Down fishing town, as well as tales of tourism, industrial heritage and sport, a dazzling mosaic of Ulster life is pieced together in unseen archive footage.
Hundreds of unique films have been released to the public to view online for free after the British Film Institute (BFI) unlocked its archive as part of a major history project, From Britain On Film.
Royal visits and Lord Mayor's shows are documented in the collection, as is the tale of Churchill's appearance in Belfast when he addressed an audience of nationalists in Celtic Park and gave his support to Home Rule.
There are also dozens of travelogues that were used to sell Northern Ireland to tourists in Great Britain and the United States, helping to boost tourism in the years before the Troubles.
And in sport, the 1930 Ulster Tourist Trophy race held at the Ards circuit in County Down is captured on camera. The event attracted thousands of spectators and commanded the attention of the motorsport world.
The real gems, however, are found in the footage of ordinary people doing extraordinary things.
Films of people at work in the spinning mills and constructing the M1 at Stockman's Lane in Belfast shows Northern Ireland's industry at its booming best.
Another film captures the first time Northern Ireland hosted the World Ploughing Championships, and fittingly it is a local man who takes the title.
The colour footage from the 1959 competition in Armoy, County Antrim, shows Lawrence McMillan's crowning moment as he gets his hands on the Golden Plough.
But perhaps most revealing of all is a 1938 recording of the Royal Victoria Hospital in Belfast.
It gives a rare glimpse into the casualty department and operating theatres as they were then, 10 years before the foundation of the National Health Service.
While medicine has advanced considerably in the eight decades since then, some aspects of healthcare in Northern Ireland appear to remain unchanged - the film ends with an appeal from the chairman of the hospital's management board to reduce waiting lists.
Francis Jones, of Northern Ireland Screen, which gathered much of the footage, said the aim of the project was to preserve delicate film that could otherwise be lost.
"There is a pure nostalgia value to film. It's different to reading a textbook or history book," he added.
"To actually see the film has that kind of visceral appeal and really strikes a chord with people."
The full From Britain On Film archive can be viewed at the BFI Player.

Lachlan returns to the Murdoch empire as co - chairman of News Corp and 21st Century Fox , having previously stood back to focus on his own businesses . Meanwhile , younger son James was appointed co - chief operating officer at 21st Century Fox . After the phone hacking scandal , which rocked the Murdoch empire and led to the closure of the News of the World, James Murdoch had faced intense scrutiny over his leadership at News International, the UK newspaper arm of News Corp. His reputation was significantly tarnished, and the controversy derailed 21st Century Fox's (then News Corporation's) bid to fully acquire BSkyB. This period was widely seen as a major crisis for the family business, leading ultimately to the dramatic split of the old News Corporation into two distinct entities: the new News Corp, housing the publishing assets, and 21st Century Fox, holding the more lucrative entertainment businesses. James's appointment as co-chief operating officer at 21st Century Fox, alongside his brother's elevated role, signaled a strategic shift by Rupert Murdoch to solidify the succession plan and perhaps rehabilitate James's image within the company's more profitable divisions. Despite the prior setbacks, the move demonstrated Rupert's enduring trust in his sons to steer the future of the vast media conglomerate, marking a crucial transition as Lachlan and James increasingly took on operational control, preparing for Rupert's eventual step back. The focus on entertainment under 21st Century Fox allowed for a clear demarcation from the historical issues associated with News Corp's beleaguered newspaper division, aiming to project a fresh, forward-looking image for the company's global media ambitions.

Ninety - three of the retailer 's 125 stores will close , with the rest remaining open while buyers are sought . If administrator KPMG can not find buyers , the remaining stores will also shut . The chain employed 1,658 people . The chain was sold to Greybull Capital last year by supermarket Morrisons , which has said it would offer jobs to ex - My Local staff . It has struggled since being acquired by private equity firm Greybull Capital in September 2015. The chain, formerly Morrisons M Local, was sold off by the supermarket giant as part of a strategic shift away from smaller convenience formats to focus on its larger superstores. At the time of the sale, Morrisons provided significant financial support to Greybull Capital, including a loan of up to £25 million, to help stabilize the business and facilitate its turnaround. However, the investment proved insufficient to reverse its fortunes in an increasingly competitive market dominated by established players like Tesco Express and Sainsbury's Local, as well as discounters.

The challenges faced by the former Morrisons' M Local stores under Greybull Capital’s stewardship were multifaceted. High operating costs, coupled with intense price competition and shifts in consumer shopping habits, created a difficult trading environment. Despite efforts to rebrand and reposition the stores as ‘My Local’, aiming for a community-focused offering, the chain failed to gain significant traction or achieve sustainable profitability. The decision to appoint KPMG as administrators came after a period of intense financial pressure, leaving no viable path forward without significant restructuring.

KPMG's immediate priority has been to manage the closure of the 93 unprofitable stores and to seek buyers for the remaining 32. Sources close to the administration process indicate that finding a single buyer for the remaining portfolio might be challenging, suggesting that individual or smaller clusters of stores could be sold off to other retailers or convenience store operators. The closure process will unfortunately result in the loss of a significant number of the 1,658 jobs, though Morrisons' proactive offer to re-employ former My Local staff, where possible, provides some relief to those affected. This gesture by Morrisons highlights its ongoing commitment, having initially established the convenience arm and then divested it.

The collapse of My Local underscores the difficulties even established players face in the convenience sector. For Greybull Capital, this represents a significant setback, adding to their mixed portfolio of investments. The future of the remaining 32 stores hinges entirely on KPMG’s ability to secure buyers within a reasonable timeframe, failing which, they too will inevitably shut, marking the complete disappearance of the My Local brand from the high street, less than a year after its high-profile launch under Greybull.

The fine print of the deal suggests something slightly different , and shows that GM has in fact taken a hit of up to ¬£6bn in order to get shot of Vauxhall and Opel . First , a big chunk of the price - three - quarters of a billion pounds - is not for car plants , but for loans taken out by the owners of Opel and Vauxhall This unusual arrangement highlights that rather than simply selling an asset, GM is effectively paying to divest itself of a long-standing financial burden. The bulk of the £6bn charge, however, stems from the substantial pension liabilities that GM has chosen to retain rather than offload to Peugeot. Estimates place GM's retention of pension obligations for Vauxhall and Opel employees at well over £5bn, reflecting the enormous cost of legacy commitments built up over decades. This decision, made in Detroit, underscores GM's strategic imperative to clear its balance sheet of European losses that have plagued its financial performance for years. By retaining these liabilities, GM avoids the potentially complex and protracted negotiations that would have been required to transfer them to Peugeot, thereby expediting the sale and providing a clean break.

The deal, therefore, is less about GM selling a profitable division and more about a costly exit from a market where it has struggled to compete consistently. For Peugeot, this acquisition of Vauxhall and Opel presents an opportunity to significantly increase its market share in Europe and achieve substantial economies of scale. However, it also means inheriting a business that has been unprofitable for nearly two decades, requiring significant restructuring and investment to turn around. The challenge for Peugeot will be to integrate the Vauxhall and Opel operations efficiently, streamline production, and reduce costs without alienating the workforce or diluting the brands' appeal. The focus for Vauxhall under its new ownership will be on platform sharing with Peugeot models, standardizing components, and rationalizing the product portfolio to improve profitability. This move signals a definitive shift in GM's global strategy, allowing it to concentrate resources on more lucrative markets like North America and China, and invest heavily in future technologies such as electric and autonomous vehicles. The severance of ties with Vauxhall and Opel frees up capital and management attention, enabling GM to pursue its growth ambitions elsewhere, even if the price of freedom came with a hefty £6bn cheque.

The Arsenal FC midfielder , 24 , uploaded a picture from his 2014 wedding with the caption " un flwyddyn heddiw " , which means " one year [ ago ] today " . In contrast to positive responses , some users expressed confusion while others ridiculed the message . One questioned whether the FA Cup winner was " drunk " The confusion stemmed from a misunderstanding of the Welsh phrase "un flwyddyn heddiw." While perfectly natural and idiomatic Welsh for marking an anniversary – meaning "one year today" – many English-speaking social media users interpreted it literally, failing to grasp its linguistic nuance. Aaron Ramsey, a proud Welshman, had posted the picture from his 2014 wedding on what was clearly his first anniversary in 2015. However, some users assumed the caption meant the picture itself was exactly one year old, which made no sense for a 2014 wedding photo. Others simply couldn't reconcile a 2014 event with a "one year today" caption, leading them to believe the FA Cup winner was confused about his own wedding date.

The decision by Mr. Ramsey to use his native tongue, a common practice for the midfielder, was widely misinterpreted. One Twitter user, @rightjudgeiam, sarcastically tweeted, "Does Aaron Ramsey not know how long a year is? 2014 wedding, posts 'one year today'. Welsh or not, that's just bad maths." This reaction highlighted a lack of understanding regarding the traditional use of such anniversary greetings in Welsh culture. The ridicule often stemmed from assumptions that he was implying the 2014 wedding had only happened "one year today" relative to the 2015 post. This episode underscored the pitfalls of social media, where context, linguistic differences, and cultural nuances are easily lost, turning an innocent, culturally specific message into a subject of online amusement and mockery.

World heavyweight champion Fury , 27 , who expressed views on women , abortion and homosexuality , has been asked to attend a meeting in the new year . The BBBofC met to discuss the matter on Wednesday before informing Fury that he must meet with the board . The Briton has denied he is a homophobe and claimed he is " uniting the world " This upcoming meeting with the British Boxing Board of Control is expected to be a crucial one, as the organization seeks to address the widespread condemnation sparked by the boxer’s controversial remarks. Public outcry intensified following comments where Fury equated homosexuality and abortion with the end of the world, and made disparaging remarks about women.

The firestorm led to significant pressure. Over 140,000 people signed an online petition calling for the Briton to be removed from the BBC Sports Personality of the Year shortlist. Despite the controversy, the BBC maintained Fury would remain on the list, citing that the decision was based on sporting achievement. This stance further fueled debate about the responsibility of public figures.

Furthermore, his comments prompted an investigation by Greater Manchester Police (GMP). The police force confirmed they had received complaints regarding his comments, which were being assessed for potential hate crime implications. While the GMP later clarified no specific crime had been recorded, the police inquiry underscored the seriousness with which his remarks were viewed.

Fury, who secured his world titles after defeating Wladimir Klitschko, has consistently maintained that his comments were taken out of context and that he is not a prejudiced individual, insisting he respects all people. Despite his defence, the ongoing controversy has cast a significant shadow over his boxing achievements and raised uncomfortable questions for the sport. The BBBofC meeting is anticipated to clarify whether Fury will face any disciplinary action, ranging from a reprimand to a fine or even a suspension, depending on the Board's assessment of his conduct and compliance with their code of ethics.

For the first time , MPs have agreed in a vote that we will begin the process of leaving the EU by the end of March . The government chief whip was seen with a massive grin after tonight 's vote . Remember ministers ' climbdown came with a clever kicker , persuading Labour to sign up to their timetable for triggering Article 50 without committing to very much in return The 'clever kicker' was the government’s commitment to publish a Brexit white paper and allow a parliamentary debate on the negotiating strategy before Article 50 is invoked. This strategic concession offered vital political cover for Labour MPs, particularly those representing pro-remain constituencies. It enabled them to vote for the timetable, framing their support as a push for parliamentary scrutiny rather than capitulation to Theresa May’s agenda. This allowed them to appease concerned constituents and avoid accusations of obstructing the democratic will.

For Theresa May, this parliamentary triumph is paramount. It solidifies her authority over the Brexit process, demonstrating her ability to command a Commons majority for her timeline. The chief whip’s satisfaction signalled successful navigation of perilous political currents, momentarily silencing critics. This outcome strengthens May’s hand for complex negotiations with the EU, reinforcing her narrative that the UK is united in its resolve to leave by the deadline. The focus now shifts decisively from the mechanism of triggering Article 50 to defining Britain's future relationship with Europe.

However, deep divisions persist. While Labour’s leadership found a pragmatic way through, many within the party and the broader remain camp remain uneasy. The white paper offers limited real parliamentary power over final Brexit terms. Pro-remain voices will undoubtedly intensify as the immense complexities of disentangling from the EU become clearer, especially regarding single market and customs union access. The coming months will severely test the government’s resolve and party cohesion as Brexit’s true impact unfolds. This vote merely concludes the first chapter, ushering in the far more challenging phase of withdrawal and negotiation.
